            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <ol>
                <li><b>Control Board: </b>The control board, or control module, is the brain of an induction cooktop, managing all its functions and settings. It regulates the power levels, temperature, and timing, ensuring precise cooking. If the control board malfunctions, it can lead to issues such as the cooktop not turning on, error codes being displayed, or inconsistent heating. Replacing a faulty control board typically involves accessing the internal components and swapping out the old module for a new one, a task best handled by a professional technician to ensure proper installation and calibration.</li>
                <li><b>Induction Coil: </b>The induction coil is the component responsible for generating the magnetic field that heats the cookware. It is a crucial part of the induction system, and any damage or malfunction can render the cooktop ineffective. Symptoms of a faulty induction coil include the cooktop not heating or heating unevenly. Replacing an induction coil involves disassembling the cooktop to access the coil, disconnecting it from the power supply and control board, and installing a new coil. This replacement should be performed by a skilled technician to ensure safety and correct operation.</li>
                <li><b>Glass-Ceramic Surface: </b>The glass-ceramic surface of an induction cooktop is designed to withstand high temperatures and provide a smooth, easy-to-clean cooking area. However, it can crack, chip, or scratch due to heavy impacts or thermal shocks. Replacing the glass-ceramic surface involves carefully removing the damaged surface and securing a new one in place. This process requires precision to avoid damaging the underlying components and to ensure the new surface is properly aligned and sealed.</li>
                <li><b>Temperature Sensor: </b>The temperature sensor monitors the heat level of the cooking zones, allowing the cooktop to maintain precise control over cooking temperatures. A malfunctioning sensor can lead to overheating, underheating, or error codes. Replacing a faulty temperature sensor involves accessing the internal components of the cooktop, disconnecting the old sensor, and installing a new one. Proper calibration of the new sensor is essential to ensure accurate temperature readings and optimal performance.</li>
                <li><b> Cooling Fan: </b> The cooling fan in an induction cooktop helps dissipate heat generated by the electronic components, preventing overheating and ensuring the cooktop operates efficiently. If the fan fails, it can lead to overheating issues and potential damage to the internal components. Replacing a faulty cooling fan requires disassembling the cooktop to reach the fan, removing the defective unit, and installing a new one. Ensuring the fan is correctly positioned and connected is crucial for effective cooling.</li>
                <li><b> User Interface (Touch Panel): </b>The user interface, often a touch-sensitive panel, allows users to control the cooktop's settings, such as power levels, timers, and cooking zones. If the touch panel becomes unresponsive or displays incorrect information, it may need replacement. Replacing the user interface involves carefully removing the old panel and connecting a new one, ensuring all connections are secure and the panel is properly aligned. This replacement should be done with care to avoid damaging the delicate electronic components.</li>
                <li><b>Power Supply Unit (PSU): </b>The power supply unit converts the electrical power from the outlet to the appropriate voltage and current needed for the induction cooktop's operation. A malfunctioning PSU can lead to the cooktop not powering on or inconsistent performance. Replacing the PSU involves disconnecting the cooktop from the power source, removing the faulty unit, and installing a new one. Proper handling and installation are essential to ensure safety and the correct operation of the cooktop.</li>
              </ol>
              <p>Each of these replacement parts plays a vital role in the functionality and performance of an induction cooktop. Proper diagnosis and professional replacement are essential to maintain the cooktop's efficiency and safety.</p>
