                  <p>
                    If your induction cooktop is tripping the circuit breaker, it indicates there's an issue that needs to be addressed to ensure safety and proper functioning. Here are some common reasons and troubleshooting steps to help you identify and potentially resolve the problem:
                  </p>

                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <b>Overloaded Circuit:</b>
                      <ul>
                        <li>High Power Demand: Induction cooktops can draw a significant amount of power, especially when multiple zones are in use. Ensure that the circuit the cooktop is connected to can handle the load.</li>
                        <li>Dedicated Circuit: Check if your cooktop is on a dedicated circuit. If other high-power appliances are on the same circuit, it might be overloading.</li>
                      </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Electrical Faults:</b>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Short Circuit: There could be a short circuit within the cooktop or its wiring. This is a serious issue and requires immediate attention from a qualified electrician.</li>
                        <li>Ground Fault: A ground fault occurs when electricity takes an unintended path to the ground. This can also trip the breaker and may require the expertise of an electrician.</li>
                      </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Faulty Cooktop Components:</b>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Internal Components: Faulty internal components in the cooktop, such as the control board or induction coils, could cause the breaker to trip. Professional diagnosis and repair are needed in such cases.</li>
                      </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Wiring Issues:</b>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Loose Connections: Ensure all electrical connections are secure. Loose wiring can cause intermittent connections and overload the circuit.</li>
                        <li>Damaged Wires: Inspect the power cord and internal wiring for any signs of damage or wear.</li>
                      </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Breaker Issues:</b>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Faulty Breaker: The circuit breaker itself might be faulty and tripping prematurely. A qualified electrician can test the breaker to determine if it needs replacement.</li>
                        <li>Breaker Rating: Ensure the breaker rating matches the power requirements of the cooktop. An undersized breaker will trip frequently.</li>
                      </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Environmental Factors:</b>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Moisture: Ensure the cooktop and its electrical connections are dry. Moisture can cause electrical faults and trip the breaker.</li>
                        <li>Ventilation: Proper ventilation is essential to prevent overheating, which can cause the cooktop to draw more power and trip the breaker.</li>
                      </ul>
                    </li>
                  </ol>

                  <b>Troubleshooting Steps:</b>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <b>Check Power Requirements:</b>
                      <p>Verify the power requirements of your induction cooktop and ensure the circuit it’s connected to meets these requirements.</p>
